Peer-to-Peer (P2P) technology has recently enabled large-scale streaming services on top of the best-effort Internet. The success of the next-generation P2P streaming systems largely hinges on new designs delivering a higher level of efficiency, robustness and incentives. During this project, we have conducted thorough study on several major P2P systems.

1. We studied service differentiation in P2P streaming to address peer heterogeneity and provide incentives. We proposed a taxation-based P2P layered video streaming. For layered P2P streaming, we found that taxation mechanisms can be devised to strike the right balance between social welfare and individual peer welfare. Multi-hop P2P relay is inherently delay-prone. We derived the minimum delay bounds for realtime P2P streaming and proposed streaming algorithms to approach the bounds. We found that, while the P2P bandwidth sharing design is very efficient for bandwidth sensitive applications, it imposes a fundamental performance constraint for delay sensitive applications. We showed that the bandwidth heterogeneity among peers can be exploited to significantly improve the delay performance of all peers. We further proposed a simple snow-ball streaming algorithm to approach the minimum delay bound in P2P live video streaming.

2. Video-conferencing is an emerging application on the Internet. For peer-assisted multi-party video conferencing, we developed optimal helper bandwidth allocation and cross-swarm sharing algorithms to achieve system-wide service differentiation. We found that P2P can significantly reduce the workload on server, and peer bandwidth resources among heterogeneous conferencing swarms can be efficiently shared to achieve system-wide quality maximization.  For P2P one-view video conferencing, we characterize the video source rate region achievable through video relays between peers. For both homogeneous and heterogeneous systems, we establish tight universal video rate lower bounds that are independent of the number of peers, the number of video sources, and the specific viewing relations between peers. We further propose P2P video relay designs to approach the maximal video rate region.

3. We also conducted measurement study on existing video conferencing systems, including Skype, Google+ Hangout, iChat. We studied their system architecture, video and audio distribution schemes, and user quality of experience. i) While P2P is promising for voice conferencing and two-party video calls, P2P alone is not sufficient to sustain high-quality multi-party video conferencing. Ii) Conferencing server locations not only impact the delivered user delay performance, but also affect the design of loss recovery mechanism and the achieved loss resilience. iii) To deliver high-quality video telephony over the Internet, realtime voice and video generation, protection, adaptation, and distribution have to be jointly designed. iv) Compared with multi-version video coding, layered video coding can efficiently address user access heterogeneity with low bandwidth overhead. With layered coding, content-aware prioritized selective retransmissions can further enhance the robustness of conferencing quality against random and bursty losses. 

4. Video telephony is increasingly being adopted by end consumers. It is extremely challenging to deliver video calls over wireless networks. We conducted a measurement study on three popular mobile video call applications: FaceTime, Google Plus Hangout, and Skype, over both WiFi and Cellular links. our findings are summarized as following.

1) With a strong WiFi/Cellular connection, modern smart- phones are capable of encoding, transmitting and decoding high quality video in realtime;

2) Mobile video call quality is highly vulnerable to bursty packet losses and long packet delays;

3) While FEC can be used to recover random packet losses, the inability to differentiate congestion losses from random losses can trigger vicious congestion cycle, and significantly degrade user video call experience;

4) Conservative video rate selection and FEC redundancy schemes often lead to better video conferencing quality, compared with more aggressive schemes;

5) End-to-end video delay is highly correlated to end-to- end packet delay in Cellular networks, regardless of the signal strength. 

5. To address the inherent peer heterogeneity in P2P streaming, each source should have the capability to send videos with different qualities to receivers with different resource availabilities. One solution is layered coding. An alternative solution is receiver partitioning. We compared the efficiency of layered coding and receiver portioning in the context of P2P multi-party video conferencing. We found that although layered coding solutions elegantly handle bandwidth heterogeneity among users in video conferencing, they also incur significant rate and complexity overheads. We first show that any multicast tree is equivalent to a collection of depth-1 and depth-2 trees, under inbound and outbound flow constraints. We compare the achievable video rate and quality with layered coding and receiver partitioning through numerical simulations of different number of users and user bandwidth profiles. In our simulations, layered coding can always achieve the optimal video rates. Somewhat surprisingly, in most simulated cases, our receiver partitioning heuristic can also achieve video rates very close to the theoretical bounds. Because layered coding incurs substantial rate overhead, the receiver partitioning system significantly outperforms the layered system in terms of video quality.





